# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flocking-steering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Artificial intelligence (AI) in video games refers to the computational systems that control non-player characters (NPCs), generate dynamic game behavior, or simulate strategic decision-making.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In practice, the term covers a broad range of techniques drawn from computer science, control theory, and robotics rather than "true" artificial intelligence.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Moreover, academic AI—aimed at developing autonomous reasoning or learning—is distinct from game AI, whose goal is to deliver engaging, believable, and efficient behavior for players.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The term *CPU* in video games refer to the AI that control a NPC that could be a playable character in some other situations.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In general, game AI does not, as might be thought and sometimes is depicted to be the case, mean a realization of an artificial person corresponding to an NPC in the manner of the Turing test or an artificial general intelligence.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some commentators in the video game industry have claimed that advances in game AI have transformed how players interact with digital systems more broadly.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Marketing discussions sometimes attribute human-like traits to game AI—such as personality or creative autonomy—but these are often scripted behaviors designed to mimic complexity rather than emergent cognition.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game playing was an area of research in AI from its inception.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the first examples of AI is the computerized game of Nim made in 1941 and published in 1942.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite being advanced technology in the year it was made, 20 years before *Pong*, the game took the form of a relatively small box and was able to regularly win games even against highly skilled players of the game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 1951, using the Ferranti Mark 1 machine of the University of Manchester, Christopher Strachey wrote a checkers program and Dietrich Prinz wrote one for chess.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These were among the first computer programs ever written.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Arthur Samuel's checkers program, developed in the middle 1950s and early 1960s, eventually achieved sufficient skill to challenge a respectable amateur.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Work on checkers and chess would culminate in the defeat of Garry Kasparov by IBM's Deep Blue computer in 1997.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first video games developed in the 1960s and early 1970s, like *Spacewar!*, *Pong*, and *Gotcha* (1973), were games implemented on discrete logic and strictly based on the competition of two players, without AI.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games that featured a single player mode with enemies started appearing in the 1970s.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first notable ones for the arcade appeared in 1974: the Taito game *Speed Race* (racing video game) and the Atari games *Qwak* (duck hunting light gun shooter) and *Pursuit* (fighter aircraft dogfighting simulator).
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Two text-based computer games, *Star Trek* (1971) and *Hunt the Wumpus* (1973), also had enemies.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemy movement was based on stored patterns.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The incorporation of microprocessors would allow more computation and random elements overlaid into movement patterns.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Galaxian* (1979) added more complex and varied enemy movements, including maneuvers by individual enemies who break out of formation.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Pac-Man* (1980) introduced AI patterns to maze games, with the added quirk of different personalities for each enemy.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Karate Champ* (1984) later introduced AI patterns to fighting games.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *First Queen* (1988) was a tactical action RPG which featured characters that can be controlled by the computer's AI in following the leader.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The role-playing video game *Dragon Quest IV* (1990) introduced a "Tactics" system, where the user can adjust the AI routines of non-player characters during battle, a concept later introduced to the action role-playing game genre by *Secret of Mana* (1993).
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games like *Madden Football*, *Earl Weaver Baseball* and *Tony La Russa Baseball* all based their AI in an attempt to duplicate on the computer the coaching or managerial style of the selected celebrity.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Madden, Weaver and La Russa all did extensive work with these game development teams to maximize the accuracy of the games.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later sports titles allowed users to "tune" variables in the AI to produce a player-defined managerial or coaching strategy.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The emergence of new game genres in the 1990s prompted the use of formal AI tools like finite-state machines.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Real-time strategy games taxed the AI with many objects, incomplete information, pathfinding problems, real-time decisions and economic planning, among other things.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first games of the genre had notorious problems.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Herzog Zwei* (1989), for example, had almost broken pathfinding and very basic three-state state machines for unit control, and *Dune II* (1992) attacked the players' base in a beeline and used numerous cheats.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games in the genre exhibited more sophisticated AI.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games have used bottom-up AI methods, such as the emergent behaviour and evaluation of player actions in games like *Creatures* or *Black & White*.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Façade* was released in 2005 and used interactive multiple way dialogs and AI as the main aspect of game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games have provided an environment for developing artificial intelligence with potential applications beyond gameplay.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Examples include Watson, a Jeopardy!-playing computer; and the RoboCup tournament, where robots are trained to compete in soccer.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many experts complain that the "AI" in the term *game AI* overstates its worth, as game AI is not about intelligence, and shares few of the objectives of the academic field of AI.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Whereas "real AI" addresses fields of machine learning, decision making based on arbitrary data input, and even the ultimate goal of strong AI that can reason, "game AI" often consists of a half-dozen rules of thumb, or heuristics, that are just enough to give a good gameplay experience.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Historically, academic game-AI projects have been relatively separate from commercial products because the academic approaches tended to be simple and non-scalable.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial game AI has developed its own set of tools, which have been sufficient to give good performance in many cases.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game developers' increasing awareness of academic AI and a growing interest in computer games by the academic community is causing the definition of what counts as AI in a game to become less idiosyncratic.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Nevertheless, significant differences between different application domains of AI mean that game AI can still be viewed as a distinct subfield of AI.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In particular, the ability to legitimately solve some AI problems in games by cheating creates an important distinction.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, inferring the position of an unseen object from past observations can be a difficult problem when AI is applied to robotics, but in a computer game a NPC can simply look up the position in the game's scene graph.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Such cheating can lead to unrealistic behavior and so is not always desirable.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] But its possibility serves to distinguish game AI and leads to new problems to solve, such as when and how to cheat.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The major limitation to strong AI is the inherent depth of thinking and the extreme complexity of the decision-making process.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This means that although it would be then theoretically possible to make "smart" AI the problem would take considerable processing power.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI/heuristic algorithms are used in a wide variety of quite disparate fields inside a game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The most obvious is in the control of any NPCs in the game, although "scripting" (decision tree) is currently the most common means of control.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These handwritten decision trees often result in "artificial stupidity" such as repetitive behavior, loss of immersion, or abnormal behavior in situations the developers did not plan for.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding, another common use for AI, is widely seen in real-time strategy games.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding is the method for determining how to get a NPC from one point on a map to another, taking into consideration the terrain, obstacles and possibly "fog of war".
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial videogames often use fast and simple "grid-based pathfinding", wherein the terrain is mapped onto a rigid grid of uniform squares and a pathfinding algorithm such as A* or IDA* is applied to the grid.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Instead of just a rigid grid, some games use irregular polygons and assemble a navigation mesh out of the areas of the map that NPCs can walk to.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As a third method, it is sometimes convenient for developers to manually select "waypoints" that NPCs should use to navigate; the cost is that such waypoints can create unnatural-looking movement.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, waypoints tend to perform worse than navigation meshes in complex environments.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Beyond static pathfinding, navigation is a sub-field of Game AI focusing on giving NPCs the capability to navigate in a dynamic environment, finding a path to a target while avoiding collisions with other entities (other NPC, players...) or collaborating with them (group navigation).
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Navigation in dynamic strategy games with large numbers of units, such as Age of Empires (1997) or Civilization V (2010), often performs poorly; units often get in the way of other units.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than improve the Game AI to properly solve a difficult problem in the virtual environment, it is often more cost-effective to just modify the scenario to be more tractable.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If pathfinding gets bogged down over a specific obstacle, a developer may just end up moving or deleting the obstacle.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many contemporary video games fall under the category of action, first-person shooter, or adventure.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In most of these types of games, there is some level of combat that takes place.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI's ability to be efficient in combat is important in these genres.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A common goal today is to make the AI more human or at least appear so.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the more positive and efficient features found in modern-day video game AI is the ability to hunt.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI originally reacted in a very black and white manner.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the player were in a specific area then the AI would react in either a complete offensive manner or be entirely defensive.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In recent years, the idea of "hunting" has been introduced; in this 'hunting' state the AI will look for realistic markers, such as sounds made by the character or footprints they may have left behind.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These developments ultimately allow for a more complex form of play.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With this feature, the player can actually consider how to approach or avoid an enemy.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is a feature that is particularly prevalent in the stealth genre.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another development in recent game AI has been the development of "survival instinct".
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In-game computers can recognize different objects in an environment and determine whether it is beneficial or detrimental to its survival.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Like a user, the AI can look for cover in a firefight before taking actions that would leave it otherwise vulnerable, such as reloading a weapon or throwing a grenade.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] There can be set markers that tell it when to react in a certain way.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the AI is given a command to check its health throughout a game then further commands can be set so that it reacts a specific way at a certain percentage of health.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the health is below a certain threshold then the AI can be set to run away from the player and avoid it until another function is triggered.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another example could be if the AI notices it is out of bullets, it will find a cover object and hide behind it until it has reloaded.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Actions like these make the AI seem more human.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there is still a need for improvement in this area.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another side-effect of combat AI occurs when two AI-controlled characters encounter each other; first popularized in the id Software game *Doom*, so-called 'monster infighting' can break out in certain situations.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Specifically, AI agents that are programmed to respond to hostile attacks will sometimes attack *each other* if their cohort's attacks land too close to them.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the case of *Doom*, published gameplay manuals even suggest taking advantage of monster infighting in order to survive certain levels and difficulty settings.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural content generation (PCG) is an AI technique to autonomously create ingame content through algorithms with minimal input from designers.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG is typically used to dynamically generate game features such as levels, NPC dialogue, and sounds.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers input specific parameters to guide the algorithms into making content for them.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG offers numerous advantages from both a developmental and player experience standpoint.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game studios are able to spend less money on artists and save time on production.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are given a fresh, highly replayable experience as the game generates new content each time they play.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG allows game content to adapt in real time to the player's actions.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative algorithms (a rudimentary form of AI) have been used for level creation for decades.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The iconic 1980 dungeon crawler computer game *Rogue* is a foundational example.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are tasked with descending through the increasingly difficult levels of a dungeon to retrieve the Amulet of Yendor.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The dungeon levels are algorithmically generated at the start of each game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The save file is deleted every time the player dies.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithmic dungeon generation creates unique gameplay that would not otherwise be there as the goal of retrieving the amulet is the same each time.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The roguelike video game genre, derived from *Rogue*, feature games that use some type of procedural generation to provide near infinite replayability.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Opinions on total level generation as seen in games like *Rogue* can vary.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some developers can be skeptical of the quality of generated content and desire to create a world with a more "human" feel so they will use PCG more sparingly.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Consequently, they will only use PCG to generate specific components of an otherwise handcrafted level.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A notable example of this is Ubisoft's 2017 tactical shooter *Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Wildlands*.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers used a pathfinding algorithm trained with a data set of real maps to create road networks that would weave through handcrafted villages within the game world.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is an intelligent use of PCG as the AI would have a large amount of real world data to work with and roads are straightforward to create.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, the AI would likely miss nuances and subtleties if it was tasked with creating a village where people live.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As AI has become more advanced, developer goals are shifting to create massive repositories of levels from data sets.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2023, researchers from New York University and the University of the Witwatersrand trained a large language model to generate levels in the style of the 1981 puzzle game *Sokoban*.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They found that the model excelled at generating levels with specifically requested characteristics such as difficulty level or layout.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, current models such as the one used in the study require large datasets of levels to be effective.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They concluded that, while promising, the high data cost of large language models currently outweighs the benefits for this application.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Continued advancements in the field will likely lead to more mainstream use in the future.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The musical score of a video game is an important expression of the emotional tone of a scene to the player.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sound effects such as the noise of a weapon hitting an enemy help indicate the effect of the player's actions.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generating these in real time creates an engaging experience for the player because the game is more responsive to their input.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] An example is the 2013 adventure game *Proteus* where an algorithm dynamically adapts the music based on the angle the player is viewing the ingame landscape from.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent breakthroughs in AI have resulted in the creation of advanced tools that are capable of creating music and sound based on evolving factors with minimal developer input.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such example is the MetaComposure music generator.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] MetaComposure is an evolutionary algorithm designed to generate original music compositions during real time gameplay to match the current mood of the environment.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithm is able to assess the current mood of the game state through "mood tagging".
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Research indicates that there is a significant positive statistical correlation regarding player rated game engagement and the dynamically generated musical compositions when they accurately match their current emotions.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative tools similar to those used in LLMs and diffusion models like Midjourney and DALL-E have been used to generate in-game environments, and companies like Ubisoft have stated that they are experimenting with using AI to generate basic dialogue.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers at Roblox are using AI to generate 3D objects for players dubbed Cube 3D, an open-source AI that generates 3D objects based on the methods of LLMs to generate words.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI often amounts to pathfinding and finite-state machines.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding gets the AI from point A to point B, usually in the most direct way possible.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] State machines permit transitioning between different behaviors.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Monte Carlo tree search method provides a more engaging game experience by creating additional obstacles for the player to overcome.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The MCTS consists of a tree diagram in which the AI essentially plays tic-tac-toe.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Depending on the outcome, it selects a pathway yielding the next obstacle for the player.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In complex video games, these trees may have more branches, provided that the player can come up with several strategies to surpass the obstacle.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academic AI may play a role within game AI, outside the traditional concern of controlling NPC behavior.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural-content generation: Creating elements of the game environment like environmental conditions, levels, and even music in an automated way.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI methods can generate new content or interactive stories.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Data mining on user behavior: This allows game designers to explore how people use the game, what parts they play most, and what causes them to stop playing, allowing developers to tune gameplay or improve monetization.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Alternate approaches to NPCs: These include changing the game set-up to enhance NPC believability and exploring social rather than individual NPC behavior.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than procedural generation, some researchers have used generative adversarial networks (GANs) to create new content.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2018 researchers at Cornwall University trained a GAN on a thousand human-created levels for *Doom*; following training, the neural net prototype was able to design new playable levels on its own.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Similarly, researchers at the University of California prototyped a GAN to generate levels for Super Mario.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2020 Nvidia displayed a GAN-created clone of *Pac-Man*; the GAN learned how to recreate the game by watching 50,000 (mostly bot-generated) playthroughs.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Non-player characters are entities within video games that are not controlled by players, but instead are managed by AI systems.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs contribute to the immersion, storytelling, and the mechanics of a game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They often serve as companions, quest-givers, merchants and much more.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Their realism has advanced significantly in the past few years, thanks to improvements in AI technologies.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs are essential in both narrative-driven as well as open-world games.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They help convey the lore and context of the game, making them pivotal to world-building and narrative progression.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, an NPC can provide critical information, offer quests, or simply populate the world to add a sense of realism to the game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, their role as quest-givers or merchants makes them integral to the gameplay loop, giving players access to resources, missions, or services that enable further progression.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, NPCs can be designed to serve functional roles in games, such as a merchant or to provide a service to the player.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These characters are central to facilitating game mechanics by acting as intermediaries between the player and in-game systems.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academics say the interactions between players and NPCs are often designed to be straightforward but contextually relevant, ensuring that the player receives necessary feedback or resources for gameplay continuity.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in artificial intelligence have significantly enhanced the complexity and realism of NPCs.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before these advancements, AI operated on pre-programmed behaviors, making them predictable and repeatable.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With AI developing NPCs have become more adaptive and able to dynamically respond to players.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts think the integration of deep learning and reinforcement learning techniques has enabled NPCs to adjust their behavior in response to player actions, creating a more interactive and personalized gameplay experience.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such development is the use of adaptive behavior models.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These allow NPCs to analyze and learn from players decisions in real time.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This behavior allows for a much more engaging experience.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example as said by experts in the field, NPCs in modern video games can now react to player actions with increased sophistication, such as adjusting their tactics in combat or changing their dialogue based on past interactions.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] By using deep learning algorithms these systems emulate human-like decisions-making, thus making NPCs feel more like real people rather than static game elements.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another advancements in NPC AI is the use of natural language processing, which allows NPCs to engage in more realistic conversations with players.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before this NPC dialogue was limited to a fixed set of responses.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It is said that NLP has improved the fluidity of NPC conversations, allowing them to respond more contextually to player inputs.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This development has increased the depth and immersion of player-NPC interactions, as players can now engage in more complex dialogues that affect the storyline and gameplay outcomes.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, deep learning models have allowed NPCs to become more capable of predicting players behaviors.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Deep learning allows NPCs to process large amounts of data and adapt to player strategies, making interactions with them less predictable and more varied.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This creates a more immersive experience, as NPCs are now able to "learn" from player behavior, which provides a greater sense of realism within the game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have led to more complex and adaptive behaviors in non-playable characters (NPCs).
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, AI systems now utilize sophisticated techniques such as decision trees and state machines to enhance NPC interactions and realism, as discussed in "Artificial Intelligence in Games".
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have also focused on improving dynamic and adaptive behaviors in NPCs.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, recent research has explored the use of complex neural networks to enable NPCs to learn and adapt their behavior based on player actions, enhancing the overall gaming experience.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This approach is detailed in the IEEE paper on "AI Techniques for Interactive Game Systems".
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite all of these advancements in NPC AI, there are still significant challenges that developers face in designing NPCs.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They need to balance realism, functionally, and players expectations.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The key challenge is to make sure that NPCs enhance the players experience, rather than disturb the gameplay.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Overly realistic NPCs that behave unpredictably can frustrate players by hindering progression or breaking immersion.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Conversely, NPCs that are too predictable or simplistic may fail to engage players, reducing the overall effectiveness of the game's narrative and mechanics.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another factor that needs to be accounted for is the computation cost of implementing advanced AI for NPCs.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of these Advanced AI techniques requires large amount of processing power, which can limit its usage.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Balancing the performance of AI-driven NPCs with the game's overall technical limitations is crucial for ensuring smooth gameplay.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts mentioned how developers must allocate resources efficiently to avoid overburdening the game's systems, particularly in large, open-world games where numerous NPCs must interact with the player simultaneously.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Finally, creating NPCs that can respond dynamically to a wide range of player behaviors remains a difficult task.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs must be able to handle both scripted interactions and unscripted scenarios where players may behave in unexpected ways.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Designing NPCs capable of adapting to such variability requires complex AI models that can account for numerous possible interactions, which can be resource-intensive and time-consuming for developers.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the context of artificial intelligence in video games, cheating refers to the programmer giving agents actions and access to information that would be unavailable to the player in the same situation.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Believing that the Atari 8-bit could not compete against a human player, Chris Crawford did not fix a bug in *Eastern Front (1941)* that benefited the computer-controlled Russian side.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Computer Gaming World* in 1994 reported that "It is a well-known fact that many AIs 'cheat' (or, at least, 'fudge') in order to be able to keep up with human players".
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the agents want to know if the player is nearby they can either be given complex, human-like sensors (seeing, hearing, etc.), or they can cheat by simply asking the game engine for the player's position.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Common variations include giving AIs higher speeds in racing games to catch up to the player or spawning them in advantageous positions in first-person shooters.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of cheating in AI shows the limitations of the "intelligence" achievable artificially; generally speaking, in games where strategic creativity is important, humans could easily beat the AI after a minimum of trial and error if it were not for this advantage.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheating is often implemented for performance reasons where in many cases it may be considered acceptable as long as the effect is not obvious to the player.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While cheating refers only to privileges given specifically to the AI—it does not include the inhuman swiftness and precision natural to a computer—a player might call the computer's inherent advantages "cheating" if they result in the agent acting unlike a human player.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sid Meier stated that he omitted multiplayer alliances in *Civilization* because he found that the computer was almost as good as humans in using them, which caused players to think that the computer was cheating.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers say that most game AIs are honest but they dislike players erroneously complaining about "cheating" AI.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, humans use tactics against computers that they would not against other people.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In short, cheating AI is when the game seems to break its own rules, producing impossible outcomes.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The opposite is dynamic difficulty, a structured adjustment of AI skill to maintain competition, respecting game mechanics.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some games may have a blend of both of these systems at once.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 1996 game *Creatures*, the user "hatches" small furry animals and teaches them how to behave.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These "Norns" can talk, feed themselves, and protect themselves against vicious creatures.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It was the first popular application of machine learning in an interactive simulation.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Neural networks are used by the creatures to learn what to do.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The game is regarded as a breakthrough in artificial life research, which aims to model the behavior of creatures interacting with their environment.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 2001 first-person shooter *Halo: Combat Evolved* the player assumes the role of the Master Chief, battling various aliens on foot or in vehicles.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemies use cover very wisely, and employ suppressing fire and grenades.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The squad situation affects the individuals, so certain enemies flee when their leader dies.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Attention is paid to the little details, with enemies notably throwing back grenades or team-members responding to being bothered.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The underlying "behavior tree" technology has become very popular in the games industry since *Halo 2*.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2005 psychological horror first-person shooter *F.E.A.R.* has player characters engage a battalion of cloned super-soldiers, robots and paranormal creatures.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI uses a planner to generate context-sensitive behaviors, the first time in a mainstream game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This technology is still used as a reference for many studios.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Replicas are capable of utilizing the game environment to their advantage, such as overturning tables and shelves to create cover, opening doors, crashing through windows, or even noticing (and alerting the rest of their comrades to) the player's flashlight.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, the AI is also capable of performing flanking maneuvers, using suppressing fire, throwing grenades to flush the player out of cover, and even playing dead.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Most of these actions, in particular the flanking, is the result of emergent behavior.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The survival horror series *S.T.A.L.K.E.R.* (2007–) confronts the player with man-made experiments, military soldiers, and mercenaries known as Stalkers.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The various encountered enemies (if the difficulty level is set to its highest) use combat tactics and behaviors such as healing wounded allies, giving orders, out-flanking the player and using weapons with pinpoint accuracy.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2010 real-time strategy game *StarCraft II: Wings of Liberty* gives the player control of one of three factions in a 1v1, 2v2, or 3v3 battle arena.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The player must defeat their opponents by destroying all their units and bases.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is accomplished by creating units that are effective at countering opponents' units.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players can play against multiple different levels of AI difficulty ranging from very easy to Cheater 3 (insane).
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI is able to cheat at the difficulty Cheater 1 (vision), where it can see units and bases when a player in the same situation could not.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheater 2 gives the AI extra resources, while Cheater 3 gives an extensive advantage over its opponent.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence, AI systems that can respond to prompts and produce text, images, and audio and video clips, arose in 2023 with systems like ChatGPT and Stable Diffusion.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In video games, these systems could create the potential for game assets to be created indefinitely, bypassing typical limitations on human creations.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, the 2024 browser-based sandbox game *Infinite Craft* uses generative AI software, including LLaMA.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] When two elements are being combined, a new element is generated by the AI.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2024 browser-based game *Oasis* uses generative AI to simulate the video game *Minecraft*.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* is trained on millions of hours of footage from *Minecraft*, and predicts how the next frame of gameplay looks using this dataset.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* does not have object permanence because it does not store any data.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2025 video game *AI2U: With You 'Til The End*, developed by AlterStaff Inc., used ChatGPT for the non-playable characters dialogue in the game.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence has been included to perform video upscaling of game images.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Both NVidia's Deep Learning Super Sampling (DLSS) and AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution (FSR) have included AI as part of their engine.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In March 2026, NVidia announced version 5.0 of DLSS to release later in 2026, which among other improvements, includes an AI engine that "infuses pixels with photoreal lighting and materials" as to make existing game graphics appear more realistic.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NVidia's Jensen Huang said that developers will far more control over how DLSS 5.0 would interact with their games, allowing the developer to tweak lighting and texture adjustments, and that NVidia was continuing to improve the technology before its release.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there are similar concerns in other fields particularly the potential for loss of jobs normally dedicated to the creation of these assets.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Voice actors were one of the first groups to express concern on generative AI use in video games.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The North American actor's union SAG-AFTRA had finished a strike in 2023 against television and film production companies, with the strike concluded on new contract terms that gave actors strong control over whether their voices could be used to train generative AI engines.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Shortly afterward, the union agreed to a contract with AI company Replica Studios to allow union voices to be used to train AI and used in games, with the contract assuring pay and rights protections.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While the contract was agreed upon by a SAG-AFTRA committee, many members expressed criticism of the move, having not been told of it until it was completed and that the deal did not do enough to protect the actors.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The strike concluded by July 2025 with the affected publishers agreeing to a contract that gave actors stronger control of whether their voices could be used for AI.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] To assure such content was disclosed by game publishers and avoid potential copyright issues, Valve implemented new requirements for games on Steam that the use of pre-generated AI assets or live generation via generative AI must be disclosed on the storefront page.
[src:flocking-steering/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sweeney criticized this move, as "it makes it much, much, much harder for a game developer to have a chance of success.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] Like most artificial life simulations, Boids is an example of emergent behavior; that is, the complexity of Boids arises from the interaction of individual agents (the boids, in this case) adhering to a set of simple rules.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] More complex rules can be added, such as obstacle avoidance and goal seeking.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] The basic model has been extended in several different ways since Reynolds proposed it.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] For instance, Delgado-Mata et al. extended the basic model to incorporate the effects of fear.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] Olfaction was used to transmit emotion between animals, through pheromones modelled as particles in a free expansion gas.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] Hartman and Benes introduced a complementary force to the alignment that they call the change of leadership.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] This steer defines the chance of the boid to become a leader and try to escape.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] The movement of Boids can be characterized as either chaotic (splitting groups and wild behaviour) or orderly.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] Unexpected behaviours, such as splitting flocks and reuniting after avoiding obstacles, can be considered emergent.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] The boids framework is often used in computer graphics, providing realistic-looking representations of flocks of birds and other creatures, such as schools of fish or herds of animals.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] It was for instance used in the 1998 video game *Half-Life* for the flying bird-like creatures seen at the end of the game on Xen, named "boid" in the game files.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] The Boids model can be used for direct control and stabilization of teams of simple unmanned ground vehicles (UGV) or micro aerial vehicles (MAV) in swarm robotics.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] For stabilization of heterogeneous UAV-UGV teams, the model was adapted for using onboard relative localization by Saska et al.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] At the time of proposal, Reynolds' approach represented a giant step forward compared to the traditional techniques used in computer animation for motion pictures.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] The first animation created with the model was *Stanley and Stella in: Breaking the Ice* (1987), followed by a feature film debut in Tim Burton's film *Batman Returns* (1992) with computer-generated bat swarms and armies of penguins marching through the streets of Gotham City.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] The boids model has been used for other interesting applications.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] It has been applied to automatically program Internet multi-channel radio stations.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] It has also been used for visualizing information and for optimization tasks.
[src:flocking-steering/boids] Biologist Richard Dawkins references the Boids model in his 2009 book *The Greatest Show on Earth: The Evidence for Evolution*.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Flocking is generally believed to arise from the need for cover and protection from predators in animal behavior.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] This is an emergent behaviour governed by local rules that are followed by individuals and does not involve any central coordination.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] There are parallels with the shoaling behaviour of fish, the swarming behaviour of insects, and herd behaviour of land animals.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] During the winter months, starlings are known for aggregating into huge flocks of hundreds to thousands of individuals, murmurations, which when they take flight altogether, render large displays of intriguing swirling patterns in the skies above observers.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Measurements of bird flocking have been made using high-speed cameras, and a computer analysis has been made to test the simple rules of flocking mentioned below.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] It is found that they generally hold true in the case of bird flocking, but the long range attraction rule (cohesion) applies to the nearest 5–10 neighbors of the flocking bird and is independent of the distance of these neighbors from the bird.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] In addition, there is an anisotropy with regard to this cohesive tendency, with more cohesion being exhibited towards neighbors to the sides of the bird, rather than in front or behind.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] This is likely due to the field of vision of the flying bird being directed to the sides rather than directly forward or backward.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Another recent study is based on an analysis of high speed camera footage of flocks above Rome, and uses a computer model assuming minimal behavioural rules.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Various algorithms have been introduced to aid in the study of biological flocking.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] These algorithms have different origins, from computer graphics to physics, each offering a unique perspective on the real phenomena.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Computer simulations and mathematical models that have been developed to emulate the flocking behaviours of birds can also generally be applied to the "flocking" behaviour of other species.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] As a result, the term "flocking" is sometimes applied, in computer science, to species other than birds, to mean collective motion by a group of self-propelled entities, a collective animal behaviour exhibited by many living beings such as fish, bacteria, and insects.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Flocking behaviour was simulated on a computer in 1987 by Craig Reynolds with the program Boids.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] This program simulates simple agents (boids) that move according to a set of three basic rules: separation, alignment and cohesion.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] The result, akin to a flock of birds, a school of fish, or a swarm of insects, was developed for motion picture visual effects.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] With these three simple rules, the flock moves in an extremely realistic way, creating complex motion and interaction that would be extremely hard to create otherwise.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Delgado-Mata et al. extended the basic model in 2007 to incorporate the effects of fear.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Christopher Hartman and Bedr̆ich Benes introduced in 2006 a complementary force to the alignment that they call the change of leadership.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] This steer defines the chance of the bird to become a leader and try to escape.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] An early model from the domain of physics, the Vicsek model (named after Tamás Vicsek) from 1995 gained attention in the study of flocking as a form active matter, a system where energy is continually added (unlike thermodynamic models).
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Applied to collective motion and swarming, Vicsek models demonstrate that a simpler set of rules with just fixed speed, self-propelled particles, and neighbor alignment, are able to achieve sub-group flocking and milling (vortex structures).
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] These models are attractive in physics due to their simplicity and universality.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Such models however, do not exhibit speed changes due to climbing and diving in flight, or complex phenomena such as orientation waves due to perceptual vision.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] The authors showed that the specifics of flying behaviour as well as large flock size and low number of interaction partners were essential to the creation of the variable shape of flocks of starlings.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Rama Carl Hoetzlein introduced the orientation-model in 2024 which separates the perceptual aspects of bird flight from the underlying aerodynamic model, linking these two control systems only by a heading target similar to real flight control.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] The perceptual model of each bird is orientation-based, mapped to a sphere, which more closely matches the biological vision system.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] The output of perception is a target heading angle (not a vector), which is used to control an aerodynamic model much like a flight simulator.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Energy and frequency analysis in this work bridge the study of real bird kinetics with simulation models.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] This model demonstrates emergent, spontaneous orientation waves for the first time, a key feature in flocking murmurations.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] In flocking simulations, there is no central control; each bird behaves autonomously.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] In other words, each bird has to decide for itself which flocks to consider as its environment.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] A basic implementation of a flocking algorithm has complexity $O(n^{2})$ – each bird could potentially interact and respond to every other bird.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] To limit complexity, it is assumed that birds only interact with a limited number of neighbors spatially in 2D or 3D.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] This was proven empirically in 2008 by Ballerini et al., where it was shown that Starlings typically interact with at most seven topological neighbors.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Lee Spector, Jon Klein, Chris Perry and Mark Feinstein studied the emergence of collective behaviour in evolutionary computation systems.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Bernard Chazelle proved that under the assumption that each bird adjusts its velocity and position to the other birds within a fixed radius, the time it takes to converge to a steady state is an iterated exponential of height logarithmic in the number of birds.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] This means that if the number of birds is large enough, the convergence time will be so great that it might as well be infinite.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] This result applies only to convergence to a steady state.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] For example, arrows fired into the air at the edge of a flock will cause the whole flock to react more rapidly than can be explained by interactions with neighbors, which are slowed down by the time delay in the bird's central nervous systems—bird-to-bird-to-bird.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Flock-like behaviour in humans may occur when people are drawn to a common focal point or when repelled, as below: a crowd fleeing from the sound of gunfire.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] In Cologne, Germany, two biologists from the University of Leeds demonstrated a flock-like behaviour in humans.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] The group of people exhibited a very similar behavioural pattern to that of a flock, where if 5% of the flock would change direction the others would follow suit.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] When one person was designated as a predator and everyone else was to avoid him, the flock behaved very much like a school of fish.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Flocking has also been considered as a means of controlling the behaviour of Unmanned Air Vehicles (UAVs).
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Flocking is a common technology in screensavers, and has found its use in animation.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Flocking has been used in many films to generate crowds which move more realistically.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Tim Burton's *Batman Returns* (1992) featured flocking bats.
[src:flocking-steering/flocking-behavior] Flocking behaviour has been used for other interesting applications.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] For example, consider navigating a mobile robot inside a building to a distant waypoint.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] It should execute this task while avoiding walls and not falling down stairs.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] A motion planning algorithm would take a description of these tasks as input, and produce the speed and turning commands sent to the robot's wheels.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Motion planning algorithms might address robots with a larger number of joints (e.g., industrial manipulators), more complex tasks (e.g. manipulation of objects), different constraints (e.g., a car that can only drive forward), and uncertainty (e.g. imperfect models of the environment or robot).
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Motion planning has several robotics applications, such as autonomy, automation, and robot design in CAD software, as well as applications in other fields, such as animating digital characters, video game, architectural design, robotic surgery, and the study of biological molecules.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] A basic motion planning problem is to compute a continuous path that connects a start configuration S and a goal configuration G, while avoiding collision with known obstacles.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The robot and obstacle geometry is described in a 2D or 3D *workspace*, while the motion is represented as a path in (possibly higher-dimensional) configuration space.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] A configuration describes the pose of the robot, and the configuration space C is the set of all possible configurations.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The set of configurations that avoids collision with obstacles is called the free space Cfree.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The complement of Cfree in C is called the obstacle or forbidden region.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Often, it is prohibitively difficult to explicitly compute the shape of Cfree.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] However, testing whether a given configuration is in Cfree is efficient.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] First, forward kinematics determine the position of the robot's geometry, and collision detection tests if the robot's geometry collides with the environment's geometry.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Target space is a subspace of free space which denotes where we want the robot to move to.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] In global motion planning, target space is observable by the robot's sensors.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] However, in local motion planning, the robot cannot observe the target space in some states.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] To solve this problem, the robot goes through several virtual target spaces, each of which is located within the observable area (around the robot).
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] A virtual target space is called a sub-goal.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Obstacle space is a space that the robot can not move to.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Obstacle space is not opposite of free space.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Low-dimensional problems can be solved with grid-based algorithms that overlay a grid on top of configuration space, or geometric algorithms that compute the shape and connectivity of Cfree.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Exact motion planning for high-dimensional systems under complex constraints is computationally intractable.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Potential-field algorithms are efficient, but fall prey to local minima (an exception is the harmonic potential fields).
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms avoid the problem of local minima, and solve many problems quite quickly.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] They are unable to determine that no path exists, but they have a probability of failure that decreases to zero as more time is spent.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms are currently considered state-of-the-art for motion planning in high-dimensional spaces, and have been applied to problems which have dozens or even hundreds of dimensions (robotic manipulators, biological molecules, animated digital characters, and legged robots).
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches overlay a grid on configuration space and assume each configuration is identified with a grid point.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] At each grid point, the robot is allowed to move to adjacent grid points as long as the line between them is completely contained within Cfree (this is tested with collision detection).
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] This discretizes the set of actions, and search algorithms (like A*) are used to find a path from the start to the goal.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] These approaches require setting a grid resolution.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Search is faster with coarser grids, but the algorithm will fail to find paths through narrow portions of Cfree.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Furthermore, the number of points on the grid grows exponentially in the configuration space dimension, which make them inappropriate for high-dimensional problems.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Traditional grid-based approaches produce paths whose heading changes are constrained to multiples of a given base angle, often resulting in suboptimal paths.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Any-angle path planning approaches find shorter paths by propagating information along grid edges (to search fast) without constraining their paths to grid edges (to find short paths).
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches often need to search repeatedly, for example, when the knowledge of the robot about the configuration space changes or the configuration space itself changes during path following.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Incremental heuristic search algorithms replan fast by using experience with the previous similar path-planning problems to speed up their search for the current one.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] These approaches are similar to grid-based search approaches except that they generate a paving covering entirely the configuration space instead of a grid.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The paving is decomposed into two subpavings X−,X+ made with boxes such that X− ⊂ Cfree ⊂ X+.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Characterizing Cfree amounts to solve a set inversion problem.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Interval analysis could thus be used when Cfree cannot be described by linear inequalities in order to have a guaranteed enclosure.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The robot is thus allowed to move freely in X−, and cannot go outside X+.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] To both subpavings, a neighbor graph is built and paths can be found using algorithms such as Dijkstra or A*.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] When a path is feasible in X−, it is also feasible in Cfree.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] When no path exists in X+ from one initial configuration to the goal, we have the guarantee that no feasible path exists in Cfree.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] As for the grid-based approach, the interval approach is inappropriate for high-dimensional problems, due to the fact that the number of boxes to be generated grows exponentially with respect to the dimension of configuration space.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] An illustration is provided by the three figures on the right where a hook with two degrees of freedom has to move from the left to the right, avoiding two horizontal small segments.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Nicolas Delanoue has shown that the decomposition with subpavings using interval analysis also makes it possible to characterize the topology of Cfree such as counting its number of connected components.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Given a bundle of rays around the current position attributed with their length hitting a wall, the robot moves into the direction of the longest ray unless a door is identified.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Such an algorithm was used for modeling emergency egress from buildings.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] One approach is to treat the robot's configuration as a point in a potential field that combines attraction to the goal, and repulsion from obstacles.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The resulting trajectory is output as the path.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] This approach has advantages in that the trajectory is produced with little computation.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] However, they can become trapped in local minima of the potential field and fail to find a path, or can find a non-optimal path.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The artificial potential fields can be treated as continuum equations similar to electrostatic potential fields (treating the robot like a point charge), or motion through the field can be discretized using a set of linguistic rules.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] A navigation function or a probabilistic navigation function are sorts of artificial potential functions which have the quality of not having minimum points except the target point.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms represent the configuration space with a roadmap of sampled configurations.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] A basic algorithm samples N configurations in C, and retains those in Cfree to use as *milestones*.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] A roadmap is then constructed that connects two milestones P and Q if the line segment PQ is completely in Cfree.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Again, collision detection is used to test inclusion in Cfree.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] To find a path that connects S and G, they are added to the roadmap.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] If a path in the roadmap links S and G, the planner succeeds, and returns that path.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] If not, the reason is not definitive: either there is no path in Cfree, or the planner did not sample enough milestones.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] These algorithms work well for high-dimensional configuration spaces, because unlike combinatorial algorithms, their running time is not (explicitly) exponentially dependent on the dimension of C.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] They are also (generally) substantially easier to implement.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] They are probabilistically complete, meaning the probability that they will produce a solution approaches 1 as more time is spent.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] However, they cannot determine if no solution exists.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Given basic *visibility* conditions on Cfree, it has been proven that as the number of configurations N grows higher, the probability that the above algorithm finds a solution approaches 1 exponentially.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Visibility is not explicitly dependent on the dimension of C; it is possible to have a high-dimensional space with "good" visibility or a low-dimensional space with "poor" visibility.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The experimental success of sample-based methods suggests that most commonly seen spaces have good visibility.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] A motion planner is said to be *complete* if the planner in finite time either produces a solution or correctly reports that there is none.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Most complete algorithms are geometry-based.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The performance of a complete planner is assessed by its computational complexity.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] When proving this property mathematically, one has to make sure, that it happens in finite time and not just in the asymptotic limit.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] This is especially problematic, if there occur infinite sequences (that converge only in the limiting case) during a specific proving technique, since then, theoretically, the algorithm will never stop.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Intuitive "tricks" (often based on induction) are typically mistakenly thought to converge, which they do only for the infinite limit.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] In other words, the solution exists, but the planner will never report it.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] This property therefore is related to Turing completeness and serves in most cases as a theoretical underpinning/guidance.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Planners based on a brute force approach are always complete, but are only realizable for finite and discrete setups.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] In practice, the termination of the algorithm can always be guaranteed by using a counter, that allows only for a maximum number of iterations and then always stops with or without solution.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] For realtime systems, this is typically achieved by using a watchdog timer, that will simply kill the process.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The watchdog has to be independent of all processes (typically realized by low level interrupt routines).
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The asymptotic case described in the previous paragraph, however, will not be reached in this way.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] It will report the best one it has found so far (which is better than nothing) or none, but cannot correctly report that there is none.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] All realizations including a watchdog are always incomplete (except all cases can be evaluated in finite time).
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Completeness can only be provided by a very rigorous mathematical correctness proof (often aided by tools and graph based methods) and should only be done by specialized experts if the application includes safety content.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] On the other hand, disproving completeness is easy, since one just needs to find one infinite loop or one wrong result returned.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Formal Verification/Correctness of algorithms is a research field on its own.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] The correct setup of these test cases is a highly sophisticated task.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Many algorithms have been developed to handle variants of this basic problem.
[src:flocking-steering/motion-planning] Hybrid systems are those that mix discrete and continuous behavior.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence systems consist typically of a population of simple agents or boids interacting locally with one another and with their environment.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The inspiration often comes from nature, especially biological systems.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The agents follow very simple rules, and although there is no centralized control structure dictating how individual agents should behave, local, and to a certain degree random, interactions between such agents lead to the emergence of "intelligent" global behavior, unknown to the individual agents.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Examples of swarm intelligence in natural systems include ant colonies, bee colonies, bird flocking, hawks hunting, animal herding, bacterial growth, fish schooling and microbial intelligence.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The application of swarm principles to robots is called *swarm robotics* while *swarm intelligence* refers to the more general set of algorithms.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] *Swarm prediction* has been used in the context of forecasting problems.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Similar approaches to those proposed for swarm robotics are considered for genetically modified organisms in synthetic collective intelligence.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Boids is an artificial life program, developed by Craig Reynolds in 1986, which simulates flocking.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] It was published in 1987 in the proceedings of the ACM SIGGRAPH conference.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The name "boid" corresponds to a shortened version of "bird-oid object", which refers to a bird-like object.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] As with most artificial life simulations, Boids is an example of emergent behavior; that is, the complexity of Boids arises from the interaction of individual agents (the boids, in this case) adhering to a set of simple rules.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Self-propelled particles (SPP), also referred to as the *Vicsek model*, was introduced in 1995 by Vicsek *et al.* as a special case of the boids model introduced in 1986 by Reynolds.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] A swarm is modelled in SPP by a collection of particles that move with a constant speed but respond to a random perturbation by adopting at each time increment the average direction of motion of the other particles in their local neighbourhood.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] SPP models predict that swarming animals share certain properties at the group level, regardless of the type of animals in the swarm.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Swarming systems give rise to emergent behaviours which occur at many different scales, some of which are turning out to be both universal and robust.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] It has become a challenge in theoretical physics to find minimal statistical models that capture these behaviours.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Social Potential Fields, developed in 1999 by John H.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Reif and Hongyan Wang , is one of the earliest models for Swarm Intelligence, developed for use for autonomous control of robot swarm systems that may consist of from hundreds to perhaps tens of thousands or more autonomous robots.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] It is the first paper to apply a potential field model to distributed autonomous multi-robot control.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] A Social Potential Field defines simple artificial force laws between pairs of robots or robot groups.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] These force laws are inverse-power force laws, incorporating both attraction and repulsion, similar but more general compared to the force laws found in molecular dynamics.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] As one of simplest examples, they define a force law where attraction dominates over long distances and repulsion dominates on short distances.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The force laws can be distinct between various robots.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] An individual robot's motion is controlled by the resultant artificial force imposed by other robots and other components of the system.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The Social Potential Fields approach is distributed since the force calculations and motion control can be done in an asynchronous and distributed manner.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Using specially tailored force laws, they demonstrate complex behaviors and what might be viewed as "social relations' among robots.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Therefore, the model was termed "Social Potential Fields”.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] They demonstrated by computer simulations that the method can yield interesting and useful behaviors among robots, including clustering, guarding, escorting, patrolling, etc.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The 1999 paper envisioned many industrial and military applications such as assembling, transporting, hazardous inspection. patrolling, and military control of swarm systems.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Their simulations showed the social potential fields method is robust in that the method can tolerate errors in sensors and actuators.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The Social Potential Fields paper also extended the social potential fields model to use spring laws as force laws.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Evolutionary algorithms (EA), particle swarm optimization (PSO), differential evolution (DE), ant colony optimization (ACO) and their variants dominate the field of nature-inspired metaheuristics.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] This list includes algorithms published up to circa the year 2000.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] A large number of more recent metaphor-inspired metaheuristics have started to attract criticism in the research community for hiding their lack of novelty behind an elaborate metaphor.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] For algorithms published since that time, see List of metaphor-based metaheuristics.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Popular modern post-2000 examples include Grey Wolf Optimization (GWO), which replicates the dynamic hunting mechanisms and social leadership hierarchies of wolves in nature.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Metaheuristics lack a confidence in a solution.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] When appropriate parameters are determined, and when sufficient convergence stage is achieved, they often find a solution that is optimal, or near close to optimum – nevertheless, if one does not know optimal solution in advance, a quality of a solution is not known.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] In spite of this obvious drawback it has been shown that these types of algorithms work well in practice, and have been extensively researched, and developed.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] One such instance is Ant-inspired Monte Carlo algorithm for Minimum Feedback Arc Set where this has been achieved probabilistically via hybridization of Monte Carlo algorithm with Ant Colony Optimization technique.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Ant colony optimization (ACO), introduced by Dorigo in his doctoral dissertation, is a class of optimization algorithms modeled on the actions of an ant colony.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] ACO is a probabilistic technique useful in problems that deal with finding better paths through graphs.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Artificial 'ants'—simulation agents—locate optimal solutions by moving through a parameter space representing all possible solutions.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Natural ants lay down pheromones directing each other to resources while exploring their environment.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The simulated 'ants' similarly record their positions and the quality of their solutions, so that in later simulation iterations more ants locate for better solutions.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Particle swarm optimization (PSO) is a global optimization algorithm for dealing with problems in which a best solution can be represented as a point or surface in an n-dimensional space.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Hypotheses are plotted in this space and seeded with an initial velocity, as well as a communication channel between the particles.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Particles then move through the solution space, and are evaluated according to some fitness criterion after each timestep.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Over time, particles are accelerated towards those particles within their communication grouping which have better fitness values.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The main advantage of such an approach over other global minimization strategies such as simulated annealing is that the large number of members that make up the particle swarm make the technique impressively resilient to the problem of local minima.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Artificial Swarm Intelligence (ASI) is method of amplifying the collective intelligence of networked human groups using control algorithms modeled after natural swarms.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] ASI has also been used to enable groups of doctors to generate diagnoses with significantly higher accuracy than traditional methods.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] ASI has been used by the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) of the United Nations to help forecast famines in hotspots around the world.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Swarm Intelligence-based techniques can be used in a number of applications.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The U.S. military is investigating swarm techniques for controlling unmanned vehicles.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The European Space Agency is thinking about an orbital swarm for self-assembly and interferometry.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] NASA is investigating the use of swarm technology for planetary mapping.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Bekey discusses the possibility of using swarm intelligence to control nanobots within the body for the purpose of killing cancer tumors.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Conversely al-Rifaie and Aber have used stochastic diffusion search to help locate tumours.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence (SI) is increasingly applied in Internet of Things (IoT) systems, and by association to Intent-Based Networking (IBN), due to its ability to handle complex, distributed tasks through decentralized, self-organizing algorithms.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence has also been applied for data mining and cluster analysis.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Ant-based models are further subject of modern management theory.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence can be used in many practical areas where multiple simple agents work together to solve complex problems efficiently.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] It is commonly applied in optimization problems, such as route planning, scheduling, and resource allocation, where algorithms inspired by ants and birds help find the best solutions.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] In robotics, swarm intelligence is used for coordinating multiple robots in tasks like search and rescue, warehouse automation, and environmental monitoring.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] It is also widely used in network systems for efficient routing of data in the internet and wireless sensor networks.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] In addition, swarm intelligence plays an important role in traffic and transportation systems, where it helps in traffic signal control, vehicle routing, and reducing congestion in smart cities.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] In machine learning and data mining, it is used for feature selection, clustering, and improving model performance.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] It is also applied in power systems for load balancing and energy optimization, especially in smart grids.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Furthermore, swarm intelligence is used in healthcare and bioinformatics for tasks like drug discovery and gene analysis, and in gaming and simulations to create realistic group behaviors such as crowd movement or flocking.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The use of swarm intelligence in telecommunication networks has also been researched, in the form of ant-based routing.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] This was pioneered separately by Dorigo et al. and Hewlett-Packard in the mid-1990s, with a number of variants existing.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Basically, this uses a probabilistic routing table rewarding/reinforcing the route successfully traversed by each "ant" (a small control packet) which flood the network.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] As the system behaves stochastically and is therefore lacking repeatability, there are large hurdles to commercial deployment.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Mobile media and new technologies have the potential to change the threshold for collective action due to swarm intelligence (Rheingold: 2002, P175).
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The location of transmission infrastructure for wireless communication networks is an important engineering problem involving competing objectives.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] A minimal selection of locations (or sites) are required subject to providing adequate area coverage for users.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] A very different, ant-inspired swarm intelligence algorithm, stochastic diffusion search (SDS), has been successfully used to provide a general model for this problem, related to circle packing and set covering.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] It has been shown that the SDS can be applied to identify suitable solutions even for large problem instances.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Airlines have also used ant-based routing in assigning aircraft arrivals to airport gates.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] At Southwest Airlines a software program uses swarm theory, or swarm intelligence—the idea that a colony of ants works better than one alone.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Each pilot acts like an ant searching for the best airport gate.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] "The pilot learns from his experience what's the best for him, and it turns out that that's the best solution for the airline," Douglas A.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] As a result, the "colony" of pilots always go to gates they can arrive at and depart from quickly.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The program can even alert a pilot of plane back-ups before they happen.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] "We can anticipate that it's going to happen, so we'll have a gate available," Lawson says.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Artists are using swarm technology as a means of creating complex interactive systems or simulating crowds.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Tim Burton's *Batman Returns* also made use of swarm technology for showing the movements of a group of bats.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Airlines have used swarm theory to simulate passengers boarding a plane.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Southwest Airlines researcher Douglas A.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Lawson used an ant-based computer simulation employing only six interaction rules to evaluate boarding times using various boarding methods.(Miller, 2010, xii-xviii).
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Networks of distributed users can be organized into "human swarms" through the implementation of real-time closed-loop control systems.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Developed by Louis Rosenberg in 2015, human swarming, also called artificial swarm intelligence, allows the collective intelligence of interconnected groups of people online to be harnessed.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The collective intelligence of the group often exceeds the abilities of any one member of the group.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] In one such study, swarms of human radiologists connected together were tasked with diagnosing chest x-rays and demonstrated a 33% reduction in diagnostic errors as compared to the traditional human methods, and a 22% improvement over traditional machine-learning.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The University of California San Francisco (UCSF) School of Medicine released a preprint in 2021 about the diagnosis of MRI images by small groups of collaborating doctors.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The study showed a 23% increase in diagnostic accuracy when using Artificial Swarm Intelligence (ASI) technology compared to majority voting.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Swarm grammars are swarms of stochastic grammars that can be evolved to describe complex properties such as found in art and architecture.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] These grammars interact as agents behaving according to rules of swarm intelligence.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Such behavior can also suggest deep learning algorithms, in particular when mapping of such swarms to neural circuits is considered.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The "creativity" of this hybrid swarm system has been analysed under the philosophical light of the "rhizome" in the context of Deleuze's "Orchid and Wasp" metaphor.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] A more recent work of al-Rifaie et al., "Swarmic Sketches and Attention Mechanism", introduces a novel approach deploying the mechanism of 'attention' by adapting SDS to selectively attend to detailed areas of a digital canvas.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Once the attention of the swarm is drawn to a certain line within the canvas, the capability of PSO is used to produce a 'swarmic sketch' of the attended line.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The swarms move throughout the digital canvas in an attempt to satisfy their dynamic roles—attention to areas with more details—associated with them via their fitness function.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Having associated the rendering process with the concepts of attention, the performance of the participating swarms creates a unique, non-identical sketch each time the 'artist' swarms embark on interpreting the input line drawings.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] In other works, while PSO is responsible for the sketching process, SDS controls the attention of the swarm.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] In a similar work, "Swarmic Paintings and Colour Attention", non-photorealistic images are produced using SDS algorithm which, in the context of this work, is responsible for colour attention.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] The "computational creativity" of the above-mentioned systems are discussed in through the two prerequisites of creativity (i.e. freedom and constraints) within the swarm intelligence's two infamous phases of exploration and exploitation.
[src:flocking-steering/swarm-intelligence] Michael Theodore and Nikolaus Correll use swarm intelligent art installation to explore what it takes to have engineered systems to appear lifelike.
